<p><pb

n="3r"/><!--
I number the pages of these Belora plates as they would have stood in a three-plate document, though I restart line numbers in each.
--><lb
n="1"/>Ucitā<choice><sic>ś</sic><corr>ṁ</corr></choice> cāsya pūrvva-rājānumatāṁ cāturvvaidya-grāma-maryyādā<choice><sic>n</sic><corr>m</corr></choice> vitarāmas<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> tad yathā A-kara-dāyi
<lb
n="2"/>A-bhaṭa-cch<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>tra-prāveśya A-pārampara-go-balivarddaḥ A-puṣpa-kṣ<choice><sic>i</sic><corr>ī</corr></choice>ra-sandoha A-cārāsana-ca<lb
n="3" break="no"/>rmmāṅgāra A-lavaṇa-<space type="binding-hole"/>klinna-kleṇi-khanakaḥ sarvva-veṣṭi-parihāra-parihr̥taḥ sa-nidhiḥ sopa<lb
n="4" break="no"/>nidhiḥ sa-k<choice><sic>li</sic><corr>l̥</corr></choice>ptopak<choice><sic>li</sic><corr>l̥</corr></choice>pta <choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>candrāditya-kālīya<unclear>ḥ</unclear> putra-pautrānugāmikaḥ bhuñjat<choice><sic>ā</sic><corr>o</corr></choice>
<lb
n="5"/>na kenacid vyāghāta<unclear>ẖ ka</unclear>rttavyaḥ sarvva-k<choice><sic>r̥</sic><corr>ri</corr></choice>yābhis sa<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>rakṣitavyaḫ parivarddhayitavyaś ca| yaś c<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>smac-chā<lb
n="6" break="no"/>sanam agaṇayamānaḥ svalpām api paribādhā<choice><sic>n</sic><corr>ṅ</corr></choice> kuryyāt <choice><sic>kārayira</sic><corr>kārayeta</corr></choice> vā Asya brāhmaṇair vveditasya
					<pb

n="3v"/><lb
n="7"/>sa-daṇḍa-nigraha<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> kuryyāma||<!--
In l1 Mirashi prints cāturrvaidya in CII5, but correctly with rvvai in E24.
--><!--
I do not supply endings in line 2. Mirashi carefully corrects everything to a neuter to agree with grāmadvayam, noting that the masculine forms used here were "blindly copied" from a standard text in which the donation was grāmaḥ. But on the one hand we cannot be sure at all that this plate went with a grāmadvaya donation, and on the other, we did have a masculine instead of neuter very close to grāmadvaya.
--><!--
Mirashi emends veṣṭi in l3 to viṣṭi.
--><!--
Much of this face is next to illegible in the rubbing. In l3, Mirashi corrects to kiṇva-kreṇi, but I only keep his reading of the original, which may, however, be incorrect.
--><!--
In l4 Mirashi prints a-klipto° in CII5 (emending to sa-kl̥pto°); his text is correctly sa-klipto in EI24 (so the emendation in CII5 is probably only for the l̥ and the neuter ending, and the a is a typo in the main text).
--><!--
The punctuation sign in l5 seems to be a short dash.
--><!--
The punctuation sign in l7 is a double short dash, much like a colon.
--></p>
<p>asmi<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>ś ca dharmmādara-karaṇe Atītāneka-rāja-<choice><sic>dattāṁ </sic><corr>datta-</corr></choice>sañcint<surplus>y</surplus>ana-paripā<lb
n="8" break="no"/>lana<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> kr̥ta-pu<choice><sic>n</sic><corr>ṇ</corr></choice>yānukīrttana-parihārārtthaṁ na kīrttayāmaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> vyāsa-gītau cātra ślokau pramāṇī-
<lb
n="9"/>karttavyau|<!--
In l8 Mirashi prints the anusvāra of °ārtthaṁ as supplied (in both his editions). The anusvāra seems clear in the rubbing.
--></p>
<lg n="1" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a">sva-dattām para-dattā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> v<surplus>v</surplus>ā <space/></l>
<l n="b">hared <choice><sic>vā</sic><corr>yo</corr></choice> vai vasundharā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied><space/></l>
<l n="c">gavā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> śata-sahasrasya|</l>
<l n="d">hantur ha<lb
n="10" break="no"/>rati duṣkr̥ta<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>| <space type="binding-hole"/></l><!--
L10. After duṣkr̥ta, Mirashi in EI prints a single daṇḍa and supplies another; in CII5 he prints a supplied double daṇḍa followed by an original double daṇḍa! There certainly is something after ta; it may be a very small halanta M or a punctuation sign. Given the tiny halanta T in the next verse, perhaps this is a trace of a similarly tiny M.
--></lg>
<lg n="2" met="anuṣṭubh">
<l n="a"><choice><sic>ṣaṣṭhi</sic><corr>ṣaṣṭiṁ</corr></choice> varṣa-sahasrāṇi <space/></l>
<l n="b">svargge modati bhūmi-daḥ<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied>|</l>
<l n="c">Acchettā cā<lb
n="11" break="no"/>numantā ca <space/></l>
<l n="d">tāny eva narake vaseT</l><!--
The halanta T in l11 is a very small subscript form.
--></lg>
<p>saṁvatsare <sic>ekādaśame</sic> <num value="11"><g type="numeral">10</g> 1</num> kārttika-śukla-pakṣa-
<lb
n="12"/>trayodaśyā<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> <num value="13"><g type="numeral">10</g> 3</num> sen<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>patau citravarmmāṇinā likhita<supplied reason="omitted">M</supplied>|<g type="closer"/><!--
Senāpatau in l12 is probably meant for senāpatinā, though Mirashi does not say so.
--><!--
For citravarmmāṇinā, Mirashi suggests haplography for citravarmmamaṇinā.
--><!--
The final punctuation seems to be a horizontal dash, slightly longer than those in the text. Mirashi says that "There is an ornamental mark after this [daṇḍa] followed by two daṇḍas and a horizontal stroke." Only some traces are discernible in the rubbing; the mark may be a circle consisting of about 8 dots with another dot at the centre, possibly followed by some additional verticals and a horizontal.
--></p>
